    <h2 id="key-definitions-and-terminology">Key definitions and
terminology</h2>
<p><span class="anchor" id="table-1"></span>Table 1. Key
definitions and terms used in the Fire Severity Module.</p>
<table>
<colgroup>
<col style="width: 16%"/>
<col style="width: 83%"/>
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr class="header">
<th>Term</th>
<th>Definition</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Apical resprouting</td>
<td>Foliage resprouting from the apical bud following fire. The bud is
protected by tightly clustered new leaf material and leaf bases of
mature leaves.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Basal resprouting</td>
<td>Foliage resprouting at or below ground level from lignotubers,
rhizomes, stem bases and stolons.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Black ash</td>
<td>Dark ash where an unburnt fuel component remains.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Char</td>
<td>Black carbon residue on vegetation and soil where incomplete
combustion has occurred.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Coarse woody debris (CWD)</td>
<td>Includes whole fallen trees and branches and pieces of fragmented
wood. CWD is defined here as any piece with a diameter ≥10 cm (or ≥5 cm
in some systems). CWD does not include live material, standing dead
trees, stumps, dead foliage, separated bark, non-woody pieces, roots or
the part of the bole below the root collar.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Cover</td>
<td>The percentage of the vertical projection of substrate type or
vegetation, characterised by species, growth form and height of lower,
mid and upper vegetation strata, present in a specific area (in this
case the number of point-intercept hits as a percentage of the total
number of point-intercepts).</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Epicormic resprouting</td>
<td>Foliage resprouting from dormant buds under tree bark on the primary
stem and branches following a fire. The buds, which are normally
suppressed by hormones released from the canopy, are protected by the
bark during a fire.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Fire intensity</td>
<td>The amount of energy released during the combustion process.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Fire patchiness</td>
<td>The heterogeneity of burnt and unburnt patches</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Fire severity</td>
<td>The degree of consumption and scorching of live vegetation and dead
fuel, and the degree to which soil properties and processes are altered
due to combustion.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>GRS Densitometer™</td>
<td>Instrument developed by Geographic Resource Solutions for measuring
canopy cover during point-intercept sampling. A vertical sighting tube
with crosshairs and a 45° mirror provide a quick and simple view of the
immediate canopy coverage. Internal, offset levelling vials ensure
accurate readings of the canopy directly above each point-intercept (see
the Cover module for further details).</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>In canopy sky (ICS)</td>
<td>Recorded when the vertical line of sight through the densitometer
does not intercept any part of a tree's canopy (foliage and branches)
but is within the boundary of the tree's canopy (see the Cover Module
for further details). Allows point-intercept data to be expressed as
foliage projective cover and opaque canopy cover.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Monitor</td>
<td>Field data collection app for Ecological Monitoring System
Australia. Collects data using the Biodiversity Information Standard for
delivery to the Australian Biodiversity Data Repository managed by the
Department of Climate Change, Energy, the Environment and Water.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Point-intercept</td>
<td>Method designed to sample species, growth-form, strata or substrate
cover by placing a staff along a transect at regular intervals and
determining the points that ‘hit’ (or intercept) vegetation or
substrate. Percent cover is calculated as the number of hits divided by
the total number of point-intercepts, multiplied by 100 (percent).</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Scorched vegetation</td>
<td>Vegetation killed by proximal heating without direct flame contact
(i.e. brown foliage that did not actually catch fire).</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Trimble® R1</td>
<td>A rugged, compact, lightweight Global Navigation Satellite System
(GNSS) receiver (configured with the GNSS Status app) that provides
professional-grade positioning information (sub-metre) to any connected
mobile device using Bluetooth® connectivity.</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>White ash</td>
<td>Mineral ash where fuel has undergone complete combustion.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>"""^^rdf:HTML ;
